SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 

a) Since the vertical intercept of the graph of \( y=f(x) \) is (0,$y0), we have \( f(0)= $y0 \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) Since the horizontal intercept of the graph of \( y=f(x) \) is ($x0,0), we have \( f($x0)=0 \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
c) The function \( f^{-1} \) goes from $BITALIC y${EITALIC}-values to $BITALIC x${EITALIC}-values, so to evaluate \( f^{-1}(0) \), we want the $BITALIC x${EITALIC}-value corresponding to \( y=0 \). This is \( x= $x0 \), so \( f^{-1}(0)= $x0 \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
d) Solving \( f^{-1}(?)=0 \) means finding the $BITALIC y${EITALIC}-value corresponding to \( x=0 \). This is \( y= $y0 \), so \( f^{-1}($y0)=0 \).
$BR
